{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Ribonucleotide reductase (also known as ribonucleoside-diphosphate reductase) catalyses the biosynthesis of deoxyribonucleotides from the corresponding ribonucleotides providing the precursors necessary for DNA synthesis. Three main classes of ribonucleotide reductases (RNR) have been discovered that depend on different metal cofactors for the catalytic activity: class I enzymes contain a diiron-oxygen cluster, class II a cobalt containing cobalamin cofactor (vitamin B12), and class III an 4Fe-4S iron-sulfur cluster coupled to S-adenosylmethionine (SAM) [[cite:PUB00060768]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false} {"text" "<p>This entry represents a group of adenosylcobalamin (AdoCbl or coenzymeB12)-dependent ribonucleotide reductases (Class II RNRs) related to the characterised species from Pyrococcus [[cite:PUB00020749]], Thermoplasma [[cite:PUB00020776]], Corynebacterium [[cite:PUB00016697]] and Deinococcus [[cite:PUB00020792]]. RNR's are responsible for the conversion of the ribose sugar of RNA into the deoxyribose sugar of DNA. This is the rate-limiting step of DNA biosynthesis. This model identifies genes in a wide range of deeply branching bacteria. All are structurally related to the class I (non-haem iron-dependent) RNRs. In most species this gene is known as NrdJ, while in mycobacteria it is called NrdZ.</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "3o0q", "name" "Thermotoga maritima Ribonucleotide Reductase, NrdJ, in complex with dTTP, GDP and Adenosine"}, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"cdd" {"cd02888" "Class II ribonucleotide reductase, dimeric form"}, "ncbifam" {"TIGR02504" "adenosylcobalamin-dependent ribonucleoside-diphosphate reductase"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Ribonucleotide reductase, adenosylcobalamin-dependent", "short" "RNR_NrdJ/NrdZ"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :c